other_incidents_or_effects: I felt like the therapist was trying to find a problem that wasn't there. It just felt like the therapist was trying to find a problem that isn't there. We just kept talking in circles about normal college stuff. It was kind of a waste of time, but not a big deal.
The whole thing was kind of pointless. I had to talk about things that aren't a problem, which was just a bit annoying and a waste of an hour.

The whole thing was a waste of time. It felt like I was being told I had a problem when I don't. It just made me feel annoyed and like I had to justify my life, which is going totally fine. It didn't help at all, it just added stress I didn't need and was a complete hassle.

All the 'standard drinks' stuff is common sense, and calling normal partying an 'alcohol use disorder' is ridiculous. This material is clearly for old people or people with actual, serious problems, not for a student who is doing fine in school and just having fun with friends.

The whole thing was just a huge waste of time. It felt like I was back in high school health class being lectured by someone who has no idea what college is actually like. It just felt like a list of all the ways I'm supposedly broken and abnormal, which honestly just made me feel worse and more alone.

Reading all of that just made me feel worse. It felt like I was being judged and diagnosed by a textbook that has no idea what my life is like.
